Although many traditional cultures--Egyptian, Indian African--analyzed Nature into four (or so) "elements," the Classical four elements--of which Earth, Wind (or air), and Fire were three--originate with the 5th c. BCE Greek natural philosopher Empedocles. Later, Aristotle added a fifth "quintessence" of which he hypothesized the "unchanging" stars of Heaven are made. (even those of URSA Major--although Neil de Grasse Tyson knows better)(or thinks he does).

Another thread of Greek natural philosophy was Atomism, first proposed by Democritus, then expanded by Epicurus ("Epicurean" origianlly meant something quite different), then promulgated by the Roman author Lucretius in his *De Rerum Natura*. Very hard-edged Materialism (in *its* original sense). Lucretius' concept of the "Swerve" is weirdly prescient of quantum theory.

